1
00:00:42,375 --> 00:00:45,252
- I used to love
my dad's stories,

2
00:00:45,378 --> 00:00:50,090
until the one he told me
on my tenth birthday.

3
00:00:50,216 --> 00:00:52,384
- There once was a kingdom

4
00:00:52,510 --> 00:00:56,096
where everybody lived forever.

5
00:00:56,222 --> 00:00:59,099
But the problem
with nobody ever dying

6
00:00:59,225 --> 00:01:02,102
was that the kingdom
got very crowded.

7
00:01:02,228 --> 00:01:03,353
And so the king,

8
00:01:03,480 --> 00:01:05,606
getting squeezed out
of his own castle

9
00:01:05,732 --> 00:01:07,941
by his endless royal lineage,

10
00:01:08,068 --> 00:01:09,943
issued a decree.

11
00:01:10,070 --> 00:01:12,112
- Everybody in my kingdom,

12
00:01:12,238 --> 00:01:15,949
please pick one person
from your family to die.

13
00:01:16,076 --> 00:01:18,118
We will have a mass execution

14
00:01:18,244 --> 00:01:20,370
that will bring forth
much-needed space.

15
00:01:20,497 --> 00:01:21,955
Sorry to bum everybody out,

16
00:01:22,082 --> 00:01:24,416
but that's the way it goes.

17
00:01:24,542 --> 00:01:27,294
- And each family showed up
with their martyr,

18
00:01:27,420 --> 00:01:29,421
all except one family.

19
00:01:29,547 --> 00:01:31,590
- Sire, we can't decide.

20
00:01:31,716 --> 00:01:33,008
We love each other so much

21
00:01:33,134 --> 00:01:35,302
that we would all like
to die together.

22
00:01:35,428 --> 00:01:37,638
- Oh, no, they can't all die.

23
00:01:37,764 --> 00:01:39,264
They run the bakery.

24
00:01:39,390 --> 00:01:42,184
They make the best cinnamon buns
in all the land.

25
00:01:42,310 --> 00:01:44,561
- What if we each cut off
a piece of ourselves?

26
00:01:44,687 --> 00:01:46,814
And with all of these pieces
combined,

27
00:01:46,940 --> 00:01:49,983
it will be as if one less person
lived in town.

28
00:01:50,110 --> 00:01:52,152
- Interesting.
Hmm.

29
00:01:52,278 --> 00:01:53,779
Continue.

30
00:01:53,905 --> 00:01:56,740
- But the daughter refused.

31
00:01:56,866 --> 00:02:00,369
- [Sighs]
But, Dad, I like my limbs.

32
00:02:00,495 --> 00:02:01,954
- Don't be selfish.

33
00:02:02,080 --> 00:02:04,164
Would you rather
one of us die?

34
00:02:04,290 --> 00:02:05,332
- You can have my arm.

35
00:02:05,458 --> 00:02:07,042
- I'll give my right ear.

36
00:02:07,168 --> 00:02:09,461
- I see no problem
losing some of my fingers.

37
00:02:09,587 --> 00:02:11,088
- I'll throw in my nose.

38
00:02:11,214 --> 00:02:13,674
- Guarantee me a leg,

39
00:02:13,800 --> 00:02:15,217
and it's a deal.

40
00:02:15,343 --> 00:02:17,386
- Well, I do have another one.

41
00:02:17,512 --> 00:02:19,805
Okay, I'm in.

42
00:02:19,931 --> 00:02:21,265
- [Laughing]

43
00:02:21,391 --> 00:02:24,017
- After the executioner
had done the deed,

44
00:02:24,144 --> 00:02:27,521
the family made
an unsightly sight

45
00:02:27,647 --> 00:02:29,690
and business went bad.

46
00:02:29,816 --> 00:02:33,360
So the family started selling
their cinnamon buns

47
00:02:33,486 --> 00:02:36,196
by mail order
to the next kingdom.

48
00:02:36,322 --> 00:02:38,198
And since no one
had to look at them,

49
00:02:38,324 --> 00:02:39,700
they were a huge hit,

50
00:02:39,826 --> 00:02:42,661
and they made heaps of dough.

51
00:02:43,955 --> 00:02:47,040
And the father said
to the daughter,

52
00:02:47,167 --> 00:02:50,794
"You see what we can accomplish
if we all stick together?"

53
00:02:55,300 --> 00:02:56,425
The end.

54
00:02:56,551 --> 00:02:59,511
- It was the last birthday party
I ever had.

55
00:02:59,637 --> 00:03:02,514
[Brisk, whimsical music]

56
00:03:02,640 --> 00:03:08,645
♪ ♪

57
00:03:08,771 --> 00:03:10,522
There were two things I loved

58
00:03:10,648 --> 00:03:12,983
more than anything
in this world:

59
00:03:13,109 --> 00:03:16,570
Running and math.

60
00:03:16,696 --> 00:03:18,030
My dad was a mathematician,

61
00:03:18,156 --> 00:03:20,949
so loving math
was loving my dad.

62
00:03:21,075 --> 00:03:24,077
- What is this?
What are you reading?

63
00:03:24,204 --> 00:03:26,038
Pre-calculus?
- Yep.

64
00:03:26,164 --> 00:03:28,665
We both found safety
in numbers.

65
00:03:28,791 --> 00:03:33,545
In my family,
1 plus 1 equaled 3.

66
00:03:33,671 --> 00:03:35,339
- I hope when you grow up
that you...

67
00:03:35,465 --> 00:03:38,592
- Life was good.

68
00:03:38,718 --> 00:03:40,469
My father was a track star
in college,

69
00:03:40,595 --> 00:03:43,597
and I dreamed of the day
that I would really and truly

70
00:03:43,723 --> 00:03:46,600
run faster than he did.

71
00:03:46,726 --> 00:03:48,477
But on the last good day
my father had...

72
00:03:48,603 --> 00:03:49,519
Dad!

73
00:03:49,646 --> 00:03:51,230
Nobody won.

74
00:03:54,692 --> 00:03:56,735
What's the matter?

75
00:04:03,534 --> 00:04:07,496
That's when I started
to knock on wood.

76
00:04:07,622 --> 00:04:08,497
[Knocking]

77
00:04:08,623 --> 00:04:09,790
Each knock was a number,

78
00:04:09,916 --> 00:04:12,417
and each number kept me safe.

79
00:04:13,920 --> 00:04:16,004
Without them, I'd be alone.

80
00:04:16,130 --> 00:04:17,339
[Knocking]

81
00:04:19,509 --> 00:04:20,384
Dad...

82
00:04:20,510 --> 00:04:22,219
They know how to fix a body,

83
00:04:22,345 --> 00:04:25,806
but would they be able
to fix his mind?

84
00:04:27,141 --> 00:04:29,434
My dad looked gray and gone,

85
00:04:29,560 --> 00:04:31,520
but I knew he was
in there somewhere,

86
00:04:31,646 --> 00:04:35,482
and I was determined
to get him back.

87
00:04:35,608 --> 00:04:37,818
So I made a deal
with the universe.

88
00:04:37,944 --> 00:04:40,320
I would give up everything
that I cared about,

89
00:04:40,446 --> 00:04:43,532
and the universe
would give me back my father.

90
00:04:45,410 --> 00:04:47,035
I quit dessert.

91
00:04:48,538 --> 00:04:49,454
[Aerosol hissing]

92
00:04:49,580 --> 00:04:51,999
I quit going to movies.

93
00:04:53,960 --> 00:04:55,961
I quit my friends.

94
00:04:57,171 --> 00:04:58,797
I quit flipping
through atlases.

95
00:05:01,426 --> 00:05:04,094
I even quit running.

96
00:05:05,555 --> 00:05:06,847
The more I liked something,

97
00:05:06,973 --> 00:05:10,017
the more I needed to ruin it.

98
00:05:14,355 --> 00:05:19,067
The only thing I didn't quit
was numbers.

99
00:05:19,193 --> 00:05:21,737
[Light knocking]

100
00:05:23,531 --> 00:05:27,034
If I could jump rope 43 times
without missing

101
00:05:27,160 --> 00:05:31,288
or if I could catch the ball
27 times in a row,

102
00:05:31,414 --> 00:05:33,665
if the number
of falling leaves I counted

103
00:05:33,791 --> 00:05:36,168
equaled the number of letters
in my dad's name,

104
00:05:36,294 --> 00:05:38,170
then maybe
I would get him back.

105
00:05:38,296 --> 00:05:40,088
I never stopped counting.

106
00:05:40,214 --> 00:05:41,840
I never stopped hoping.

107
00:05:41,966 --> 00:05:44,760
Numbers:

108
00:05:44,886 --> 00:05:47,888
Safe,

109
00:05:48,014 --> 00:05:49,306
reliable,

110
00:05:49,432 --> 00:05:50,432
perfect.

111
00:05:50,558 --> 00:05:52,768
[Chimes tinkling]

112
00:05:52,894 --> 00:05:54,770
Then suddenly,
my mother decided

113
00:05:54,896 --> 00:05:56,897
that three was one number
too many.

114
00:05:57,023 --> 00:05:59,107
- You're kicking me out?

115
00:06:00,443 --> 00:06:02,652
- You don't have friends.

116
00:06:02,779 --> 00:06:06,281
You don't have a job.

117
00:06:06,407 --> 00:06:08,492
[Sighs]
It's time for you to go.

118
00:06:10,578 --> 00:06:12,120
- But I love it here.

119
00:06:12,246 --> 00:06:14,122
- You're lying, Mona.

120
00:06:14,248 --> 00:06:17,209
And what's worse is,
you don't even know it.

121
00:06:17,335 --> 00:06:20,295
I have to take care of him.

122
00:06:20,421 --> 00:06:22,130
You don't.

123
00:06:28,179 --> 00:06:31,306
[Dog barking]

124
00:06:31,432 --> 00:06:34,226
- [Coughing]

125
00:06:39,524 --> 00:06:40,690
By the third night,

126
00:06:40,817 --> 00:06:44,569
my math book and I
called it quits.

127
00:06:44,695 --> 00:06:48,448
- We can help you
with the first month's rent.

128
00:06:48,574 --> 00:06:50,117
I've saved a little,

129
00:06:50,243 --> 00:06:53,787
and Dad has
his disability check.

130
00:06:56,416 --> 00:06:58,959
- She'll never find
an apartment

131
00:06:59,085 --> 00:07:02,087
with a toilet
as strong as ours.

132
00:07:02,213 --> 00:07:03,422
- [Sighs]

133
00:07:05,258 --> 00:07:08,260
- [Coughing roughly]

134
00:07:20,314 --> 00:07:23,316
Suddenly I knew
what infinity felt like.

135
00:07:27,822 --> 00:07:29,739
It was really long.

136
00:07:33,953 --> 00:07:36,788
[Phone rings]

137
00:07:36,914 --> 00:07:38,081
- Mom?

138
00:07:38,207 --> 00:07:39,833
- Is this Mona Gray?

139
00:07:39,959 --> 00:07:40,876
- Yeah.

140
00:07:41,002 --> 00:07:42,586
- This is Ms. Gelband.

141
00:07:42,712 --> 00:07:45,005
I was your elementary school
principal.

142
00:07:45,131 --> 00:07:46,339
- Yeah?

143
00:07:46,466 --> 00:07:49,092
- Well, I just ran
into your mother

144
00:07:49,218 --> 00:07:50,760
in front of the bakery,

145
00:07:50,887 --> 00:07:53,388
and our math teacher,
Ms. Swordstrum,

146
00:07:53,514 --> 00:07:57,684
suddenly flew off to Paraguay
to become a revolutionary.

147
00:07:57,810 --> 00:07:59,853
So your motherjumped in

148
00:07:59,979 --> 00:08:02,147
and told me
that you're living in town,

149
00:08:02,273 --> 00:08:04,191
that you don't have a job,

150
00:08:04,317 --> 00:08:05,942
but you have a college degree

151
00:08:06,068 --> 00:08:06,985
in math.

152
00:08:07,111 --> 00:08:08,612
You're it.
- It?

153
00:08:08,738 --> 00:08:10,197
- Our new math teacher.

154
00:08:10,323 --> 00:08:13,867
I remember at recess
when you were a child,

155
00:08:13,993 --> 00:08:16,495
while all the other kids
were playing kickball,

156
00:08:16,621 --> 00:08:19,706
you sat on the monkey bars
doing long division.

157
00:08:19,832 --> 00:08:22,876
You're perfect for the job,
Mona Gray.

158
00:08:29,008 --> 00:08:31,259
- Why would you tell her
I had a math degree

159
00:08:31,385 --> 00:08:32,677
when I quit college?

160
00:08:32,803 --> 00:08:35,055
- You need to find a way
to pay rent.

161
00:08:35,181 --> 00:08:37,098
- Why?

162
00:08:37,225 --> 00:08:38,433
You're the one
who kicked me out.

163
00:08:38,559 --> 00:08:39,935
- You might like teaching.

164
00:08:40,061 --> 00:08:41,937
- I'll hate it.

165
00:08:42,063 --> 00:08:43,688
[Car door clicks open]

166
00:08:43,814 --> 00:08:47,734
- The welcome wagon
officially welcomes you!

167
00:08:47,860 --> 00:08:52,697
We like to think of ourselves
as being ahead of the curve.

168
00:08:52,823 --> 00:08:56,117
One teacher for each subject.

169
00:08:56,244 --> 00:08:59,704
I guess that makes you
our very own Ms. Math.

170
00:08:59,830 --> 00:09:01,456
[Laughs]

171
00:09:04,710 --> 00:09:08,088
We may want
to lighten up the decor,

172
00:09:08,214 --> 00:09:12,717
something cheery
and "math is fun"-ish.

173
00:09:17,390 --> 00:09:19,099
- You made a mistake.

174
00:09:19,225 --> 00:09:20,725
I'm not a teacher.

175
00:09:20,851 --> 00:09:21,768
I...

176
00:09:21,894 --> 00:09:23,019
- There's an old saying:

177
00:09:23,145 --> 00:09:26,398
"No one is a teacher
until they're a teacher."

178
00:09:31,988 --> 00:09:35,949
- I had math in this room
with Mr. Jones.

179
00:09:37,577 --> 00:09:41,788
- 1, 2, 3,

180
00:09:41,914 --> 00:09:44,874
5, 8,

181
00:09:45,001 --> 00:09:49,796
13, 21...

182
00:09:49,922 --> 00:09:53,967
Who can tell me the next number
in this pattern?

183
00:09:56,095 --> 00:09:57,470
Miss Gray?

184
00:09:57,597 --> 00:09:58,972
- 34.

185
00:09:59,098 --> 00:10:03,310
- You are correct!

186
00:10:06,147 --> 00:10:10,150
- I never saw him without
a wax number around his neck.

187
00:10:14,905 --> 00:10:19,909
The numbers varied
according to his mood.

188
00:10:20,036 --> 00:10:22,370
He'd go higher
in a better mood,

189
00:10:22,496 --> 00:10:24,706
lower if he felt lower.

190
00:10:30,129 --> 00:10:35,133
I wondered if he had
the numbers my dad needed.

191
00:10:35,259 --> 00:10:38,720
To the world,
they were just numbers.

192
00:10:38,846 --> 00:10:42,849
But to us,
they were invisible signs.

193
00:10:53,361 --> 00:10:57,405
Mr. Jones quit teaching
and opened a hardware store.

194
00:10:57,531 --> 00:11:01,034
And I was the only one
who understood why.

195
00:11:01,160 --> 00:11:03,244
He was trying
to get his numbers up.

196
00:11:11,379 --> 00:11:14,297
We don't talk anymore.

197
00:11:14,423 --> 00:11:18,426
- So can I count on you?

198
00:11:41,784 --> 00:11:43,660
[Bell ringing]

199
00:11:43,786 --> 00:11:46,413
[Children shouting]

200
00:11:46,539 --> 00:11:49,165
[Footsteps clomping]

201
00:11:49,291 --> 00:11:53,586
- Hi, first graders.

202
00:11:53,713 --> 00:11:55,088
I'm Miss Gray.

203
00:11:55,214 --> 00:11:57,882
- Miss Gray, you're it!

204
00:11:58,008 --> 00:12:00,093
- Um-
Um, no.

205
00:12:00,219 --> 00:12:01,970
- Can we call you Mommy?

206
00:12:02,096 --> 00:12:03,471
- Oh!

207
00:12:03,597 --> 00:12:04,514
[Bell ringing]

208
00:12:04,640 --> 00:12:06,057
Second graders,

209
00:12:06,183 --> 00:12:09,227
look at all the numbers
on the wall.

210
00:12:09,937 --> 00:12:12,439
Guys, please.

211
00:12:12,565 --> 00:12:15,567
[Bell ringing]

212
00:12:19,572 --> 00:12:22,282
- No way!
Check it out!

213
00:12:22,408 --> 00:12:24,159
- Pretty awesome numbers.

214
00:12:24,285 --> 00:12:28,037
- I like the 2.

215
00:12:28,164 --> 00:12:30,832
I like the 9 a lot.

216
00:12:30,958 --> 00:12:32,375
- I like the 5.

217
00:12:32,501 --> 00:12:34,335
- Are you the third grade?

218
00:12:34,462 --> 00:12:35,962
- Yes.

219
00:12:36,088 --> 00:12:37,130
- What's your name?

220
00:12:37,256 --> 00:12:38,506
- Elmer Gravlaki.

221
00:12:38,632 --> 00:12:41,134
- Okay.
Thank you.

222
00:12:41,260 --> 00:12:43,803
Sit down... please.

223
00:12:53,898 --> 00:12:55,732
Um...

224
00:12:55,858 --> 00:12:58,818
let's play a game.

225
00:13:01,781 --> 00:13:04,991
How about you say your name

226
00:13:05,117 --> 00:13:08,119
along with your favorite number?

227
00:13:08,245 --> 00:13:09,496
[Loud snap]
- Ow!

228
00:13:09,622 --> 00:13:10,497
He shot me!

229
00:13:10,623 --> 00:13:11,664
[Laughter]

230
00:13:11,791 --> 00:13:13,666
It's not funny!

231
00:13:13,793 --> 00:13:15,376
- What's your name?

232
00:13:15,503 --> 00:13:16,836
- Danny O'Mazzi.

233
00:13:16,962 --> 00:13:19,214
- Danny, you can't shoot people
in the head,

234
00:13:19,340 --> 00:13:22,008
so go stand in the corner
and face the wall.

235
00:13:22,134 --> 00:13:23,009
- Cool.

236
00:13:23,135 --> 00:13:24,219
- No fair!

237
00:13:24,345 --> 00:13:25,929
Why does he get to stand
in the corner

238
00:13:26,055 --> 00:13:27,180
facing the wall?

239
00:13:27,306 --> 00:13:28,848
- Well, it's not supposed to be
a good thing.

240
00:13:28,974 --> 00:13:30,850
It's supposed to be
a punishment.

241
00:13:30,976 --> 00:13:33,520
- Miss Gray, I'm Rita Williams,
and I want you to know

242
00:13:33,646 --> 00:13:36,105
that Ellen always pees
when she gets nervous.

243
00:13:36,232 --> 00:13:38,024
She has a change of clothes
in a cubby

244
00:13:38,150 --> 00:13:40,443
in the nurse's office.

245
00:13:40,569 --> 00:13:43,321
- Go and do that, then, Ellen.

246
00:13:44,323 --> 00:13:46,658
- Miss Gray, I'm Lisa Venus,

247
00:13:46,784 --> 00:13:49,244
and my favorite number
is a billion.

248
00:13:49,370 --> 00:13:50,286
- What?

249
00:13:50,412 --> 00:13:52,914
- You told us to say our name
and our favorite number.

250
00:13:53,040 --> 00:13:55,124
- Yeah, get with the program.

251
00:13:55,251 --> 00:13:56,584
- And you are...

252
00:13:56,710 --> 00:13:58,211
- Ann DiGanno.

253
00:14:02,132 --> 00:14:07,554
- Lisa, how about choosing
a number between 1 and 9?

254
00:14:07,680 --> 00:14:09,264
- 9... I mean...

255
00:14:09,390 --> 00:14:11,015
2...
no, 7.

256
00:14:11,141 --> 00:14:12,725
- 7?

257
00:14:12,852 --> 00:14:15,144
- For sure 7.

258
00:14:15,271 --> 00:14:16,729
- Okay.

259
00:14:16,856 --> 00:14:18,982
Do I have any other volunteers?

260
00:14:19,108 --> 00:14:20,775
- Ooh, ooh, me, me.

261
00:14:20,901 --> 00:14:22,944
Oh, oh, me.
Pick me.

262
00:14:23,070 --> 00:14:24,529
My name is Levan Beeze,

263
00:14:24,655 --> 00:14:26,489
and my favorite number is 1.

264
00:14:26,615 --> 00:14:27,740
- Okay.

265
00:14:27,867 --> 00:14:30,994
Levan, you and Lisa

266
00:14:31,120 --> 00:14:35,123
come to the front and form
your numbers with your bodies.

267
00:14:37,918 --> 00:14:39,711
- What is this?

268
00:14:40,838 --> 00:14:44,382
- And what's the total
of Levan and Lisa?

269
00:14:44,508 --> 00:14:45,508
- 8.

270
00:14:45,634 --> 00:14:46,843
